Halve, peel and finely chop the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and finely chopped). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Cut the @cauliflower{1/2}(cut into bite-sized florets). Roughly chop the @coriander{1/2}(roughly chopped). Trim the tops from the @green beans{1}(trimmed and chopped into thirds).

Heat a splash of @oil{splash} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-low heat. Add the onion and slowly cook for ~{5%minutes}, then add the garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a few grinds of @black pepper{a few grinds}.

> If the onion starts to brown turn the heat down a bit.

Once the onion is soft, add the @curry powder{1}(curry powder mix) and mix with a #wooden spoon{}.

Stir in the @tomato puree{1}(stirred in) and then add the @chopped tomatoes{1}(diced). Season with another pinch of @salt{pinch} and a sprinkling of @?sugar{sprinkling} (if you have some). Add the @red split lentils{100%g}, the @water{200%ml} and the @vegetable stock pot{1}. Stir to dissolve the stock pot. Bring to a gentle simmer, put a #lid{} on and leave for ~{5%minutes}.

> Don't worry if the dal is drying out a little – just add a bit more water to get a looser consistency.

Remove the lid and add the cauliflower. Cook until tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

When the cauliflower is halfway through cooking add the green beans and cook for ~{6-7%minutes}.

Stir through most of the coriander and some of the @Greek style yoghurt{1/2}. Serve the dal in a #bowl{} with a dollop of Greek yoghurt and add the remaining coriander sprinkled on top. Enjoy!

> At this stage it's crucial to taste for seasoning - have a spoonful and add more salt and pepper to lift the flavours to their max!